# Separate Categorical and Continous Data
def cat_finder(df):
    cat = []
    cont = []
    cols = list(df.columns)
    for col in cols:
        t = df[col].dtype #returns the type of the feature
        if (t=='O'):
            cat.append(col)
        else :
            cont.append(col)
      
    return (cat, cont)
In [416]:

print("\nCategorical Features:", cat)
print("\nContinuous Features:\n", cont)

# Find distributions of the continuous features


def plot_dist(df,cont):
    for x in cont:
        plt.figure(figsize=(6,3))
        sns.kdeplot(df[x], legend=False, color="red", shade=True)
        plt.title("Distribution of "+x)
        plt.show()
        
plot_dist(df,cont)

#Variables with correlations above .7

used = []
corrs = []
for i, j in enumerate(df.corr().columns):
    for k in range(len(df.corr())):
        if ((df.corr().iloc[k, i] > .7 ) & 
            (j not in used) &
            (j != df.corr().index[k])):
            
            used.append(j)
            corrs.append((j, df.corr().index[k], 
                          np.round(df.corr().iloc[k, i], 2)))

            
corrsdf = pd.DataFrame([[i[0] for i in corrs],
                        [i[1] for i in corrs],
                        [i[2] for i in corrs]])

corrsdf = corrsdf.T.rename(columns = {0:'column',1:'row',2:'corr'})
corrsdf.sort_values('corr', ascending=False)

# Total number of employees working
TotalEmployees = df.shape[0]
# Total number of employees who left
TotalAttrition = df['Attrition'].value_counts()[1]

#percentage of employees who left out of the total 100%
AttritionRate = (TotalAttrition/TotalEmployees)*100

#number of Active employees
ActiveEmployees = (TotalEmployees - TotalAttrition)


print("Attrition Rate:", round(AttritionRate,2))
print("Active Employees:", ActiveEmployees)

Attrition Rate: 16.12
Active Employees: 1233

# Countplots for Attrition
df_col=df.drop(['EmployeeNumber','EmployeeCount','StandardHours','Age','DailyRate','DistanceFromHome','HourlyRate','MonthlyIncome','MonthlyRate','TotalWorkingYears','YearsAtCompany'],axis=1)
def plot_count(cont):
    for z in cont:
     sns.countplot(y=z,data=df,hue='Attrition')
     plt.title("Attrition By "+z)
     plt.show()
plot_count(df_col)
